looking at bi- and multilingual speakers. In this vein, the present book aims to contribute to the existing debate of the relationship between language, culture and cognition by assessing differences and similarities between monolingual and bilingual language acquisition and use. In particular, it investigates the effect of conceptual-semantic and pragmatic properties of constructions on code choice and code switching, as well as the impact of bilingual and bicultural education on speakers’ cognitive development. This collective volume systematises, reviews, and promotes a range of theoretical perspectives and research techniques that currently inform work across the disciplines of bilingualism and code switching.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBilingualismxPsychological aspects. 0aCognitive grammar. 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aSemanticsxPsychological aspects. 4aBilingualism/Biculturalism. 4aCode Switching/Mixing. 4aCognitive Linguistics. 4aEinsprachigkeit. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aLanguage Acquisition. 4aZweisprachigkeit. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aReif, Monika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobinson, Justyna A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2016z9783110485257oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97815015004040 cprintz978161451585240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161451419040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781614514190423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781614514190.jpg  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016 